Title: The Quiet Pulse
Credit: written by
Author: brehon
Source: generated from a metaphor DAG

WAREHOUSE_NUMBNESS

Eli sits alone at a metal folding table in a warehouse bay, wearing gloves, tightening bolts on a disarmed IED while rain streaks the high windows behind him

SHOULDER_TOUCH

Eli places a hand on his daughter’s shoulder; she flinches. He does not pull back. Does not blink. Does not shift his weight.

ELI
You’re safe. I’m here.

DOOR_LOCK_DROP_KEY

Eli walks out the front door of his trailer, locks it with a master key, and drops the key into a rusted oil can on the porch step.

LILY
Dad… it’s just a smoke alarm.

Eli stands in the kitchen with his right hand holding his daughter’s left hand and his left hand holding a disassembled C-4 block with its plastic casing split open along one seam. His daughter’s eyes are open wide. His eyes are open wide. The stove timer shows 12:03.

FIRST_FEAR_REGISTER

Eli’s pupils dilate. His breath catches. His hand trembles—not from fatigue, but from a new, unwelcome awareness. He turns toward the sound of his daughter’s voice calling from down the hall.

MICROWAVE_EXPLOSION_DIVE

Eli drops to one knee, wraps his arms around his daughter’s waist, and pulls her behind the kitchen island just as the microwave door bursts inward in a shower of sparks and shattered plastic.

ELI
Don’t move.

SHATTERED_GLOVE_GRIP

Eli’s gloved hands grip his daughter’s face, turning her away from the smoke. His voice cracks—first time in ten years. He does not wipe his eyes.

ELI
I’m sorry. I’m sorry. I’m sorry.
